{"/service/ndnp/deu/batch_deu_groot_ver01/data/sn87062224/0051415689A/1957112901/0007.xml":{"full_text":"i\nAutumn\nH| Activities\nA\nvV\nK\n1\nColumn of Social\nEvents Occurring\nDuring the Past\nWeek\n>5\n\u00c9\n\u00c7\n\nI\nI?\nf\nI\nEdited by\nVirginia S. Townsend\nONDAY Is an impor\ntant day on the cal\nendar of the Milford\nNew Century Club\nfor it is Health Day,\nMrs. Laurence Fitchett is\nchairman of the program and\nhas arranged an interesting\none for the members. Dr.\nGeorge Campana and Mrs. Vic\ntoria Worden of the Cancer\nControl Division of the State\nBoard of Health will be pres\nent to speaker and will show\nthe latest film release on the\nwork. This subject is of up\nmost importance to women, as\nwell as men, and Dr. Campana\nwill speak of the late progress\nin the control of the disease.\nA question and answer period\nwill follow the film and the\ntalks. Mrs. James Homan will\nbe the soloist for the afternoon.\nMr. and Mrs. Roland David\nIsaacs have issued invitations\nto the wedding of their daugh\nter, Svea Marian, to Mr. Robert\nCraighead of Buffalo, N. Y. The\nceremony will take place in\nAvenue Methodist Church on\nSaturday, December 14, 1957,\nat three o'clock.\n\nA\nMr. and Mrs. LeRoy Rust had\nopen house at their home at\nHaven Lake Wednesday eve\nning, honoring Miss Svea Isa\nacs, whose wedding to Mr.\nRobert Craighead will take\nplace December 14. Friends\nfrom out of town and those\nclose by were present to meet\nMr. Craighead and to enjoy the\nhours from nine until eleven\no'clock.\nPersonal Mention\nRichard Pack is home for the\nholiday week-end from Georgetown\nPrep School. His guest is Albin\nProvosty. of Alexandria, Va.\nSocial Security News\n\"Farm-City Week, which is be\ning observed nation-wide this week\ngives us an opportunity to stress\nthe part old-age, survivors, and\ndisability insurance is playing in\nthe American way of life,\" Myron\nMilbouer, district manager of the\nWilmington social security office,\nannounced today.\nThe Social Security Administra\ntion, through the Wilmington office,\nis cooperating with farm and busi\nness industries in this year's ob\nservance of Farm-City Week.\n\"We of the Social Security Ad\nministration are in accord with\nPresident Eisenhower who, in his\n1957 proclamation of Farm-City\nWeek said:\nall citizens, rural and urban, should\nrecognize their interdependence in\ncontributing to the strength, char\nacter, and prosperity of our Na\ntion',\" Milbouer declared.\nHe pointed out that the problem\nof family income in case the bread\nwinner's earnings are cut off by\nold-age. disability, or death Is com\nmon to both city and farm workers.\n\"Social security is designed to help\nsolve this problem, but there is\nstill need for people to understand\nthat the program applies to city\nand country folks alike,\" he said.\nMilbouer believes that many far\nmers feel that social security for\nthem is a \"special\" program. This\nis especially true' where retirement\nbenefits are concerned, he said.\nMuch of the misunderstanding is\ndue to the fact that farmers, un\nlike most city people, continue to\nlive at their place of business af\nter retiring from full activity. The\nlocal manager pointed out, how\never. that farmers are subject to\nthe same restrictions on receiving\nsocial security benefits when they\nhave earnings after retirement as\nare other beneficiaries of the pro\ngram.\nEmphasizing that old-age insur\nance payments for the farmer are\nnot a farm subsidy, Milbouer point\ned out that a farmer's right to con\ntinue to receive old-age insurance\nbenefits after retirement will be\ngoverned by the amount of his ear\nnings and the time devoted to farm\nactivities during his years of re\ntirement. The law permits him to\ntaper-off in work, work part-time\nor seasonally without losing all or\nany of his monthly payments. This\nprovision is the same as that ap\nplying to social security benefi\nciaries who work in cities after\ntheir retirement, he said.\nit is fitting that\n\nSHOP AND SAVE IN MILFORD!\nBargains Galore In Every Store!\ni\nCONTENTION CANCELLED\nLUTON. England (CP) The\nMayor of this Bedfordshire town\ninvited 107-year-old Mrs. Hannah\nTaylor and \"all her family\" to tea.\nThen discovered the potential\nguests numbered 200. The invita\ntion was cut down to Mrs. Taylor,\nher children and grandchildren\u2014\na mere 23.\n\u2022t\nMr. and Mrs. Carlton Fisher\nwelcomed their second daugh\nter in Memorial Hospital on\nFriday, November 15. She has\nbeen named Nancy Jean. Their\nfirst daughter is Debra Anne.\nMrs. Fisher was the former\nMiss Phyllis Wilkins.\n\nPreston Dyer suffered many\npainful injuries Saturday eve\nning when his car was over\nturned by another car at the\nentrance to Hall Place, where\nhe lives. A broken pelvis, a\nnumber of ribs broken and a\nlong cut along the side of his\nneck are the major things that\nplaced him in Memorial Hospi\ntal as a very sick patient. His\nfriends are hoping there will\nbe no later injuries to be dis\ncovered and that his recovery\nwill go along speedily and well.\na\nMr. and Mrs. M.\nPierce were the honered guests\nSunday afternoon at five when\nMr. and Mrs. Theodore Town\nsend and Mr. and Mrs. Robert\nBaechler entertained at the\nhome of the former on School\nPlace. It was the fortieth wed\nding anniversary of their par\nents and members of the fam\nily and a few close friends\nwere invited for buffet supper.\nA beautiful silver tea set, the\ngift of the groom to his bride\nand a beautiful wedding cake\nmade the table lovely, as the\nguests were served. Seven\ngrandchildren helped to make\nthe affair a lively one and the\nhours slipped by, pleasantly\nspent.\nHaswell\nLocal Happenings\nHOLIDAY FAIR\nret C. Pyle Rebekah Lodge will\nhold their annual fair on Friday\nand Saturday, December 6th and\n7th, in the store formerly occupied\nby Phillips Mens Shop, North Wal\nnut Street, Milford.\nThe Marga\nHAM OYSTER SUPPER A\nHam and Oyster Supper, Family\nStyle, will be served in Fellowship\nHall of Avenue Methodist Church,\nWednesday, December 4th, by Ave\nnue Methodist Men. Serving starts\nat 6:00 p. m. All you can eat\u2014Ad\nults, $1.50; Children, under 12\nyears, 65c.\nLEGION DANCE On Novem\nber 27, 1957, the local Post No.\n3 will hold a Thanksgiving Dance\nin the American Legion Home from\n9 p. m. until 1 a. m. Music will be\nprovided by Bernie Grier and his\nOrchestra. Price of admission is\n$4.00 per couple. Cabaret style will\nbe used and dress is optional. Don't\nforget!\nHOLIDAY FAIR The Margaret\nC. Pyle Rebekah Lodge will hold\ntheir Holiday Fair in the store for\nmally occupied by Philip's Men's\nStore, on Dec. 6th and 7th. Mrs.\nDouglas Fry and Mrs. Roy Lafon\ntaine are co-chairmen of this event.\nMrs. Fry is also in charge of the\nFancy Work Booth. Mrs. John\nPrettyman is in charge of the\nChristmas booth, Mrs. Harold\nBunting is in charge of the food\nbooth and Mrs. Rubeln Brigers and\nMrs. Ella Warren will have a par\ncel post booth. All the members\nof the lodge are working with these\nchairmen. Mrs. Fry had donated\nan oil painting to the lodge for the\nfair, which may be seen in the win\ndow of the Sherwin-Williams Paint\nStore. The public is cordially in\nvited to attend our fair.\nSussex County\nFiremen Meet\nThe regular meeting of the Sus\nsex County Volunteer Firemen's\nAssociation was held as guests of\nthe Lewes Volunteer Fire Company\nwith President W'illiam Lowe pre\nsiding. Invocoation by County\nChaplain, Dr. T. C. Mulligan of\nGeorgetown. President Winfield\nBrittingham of Lewes Volunteer\nFire Company gave address of wel\ncome. The three fire prevention\nqueens from Virginia, Maryland\nand Delaware were present as Miss\nBetty Nock of Virginia, Miss Betty\nLou Hammond of Maryland and\nMiss Patricia Peters of Delaware.\nChairman Ray Trice of Fire Pre\nvention Committee presented\nchecks to essay winner. Grace\nWhite of Laurel, first prize; Lor\netta Lynch of Gumboro, second\nprize, and Dianna Isaacs, third\nprize.\nPresident C. W. Ennis of Ellen\ndale, of Sussex County Fire Chiefs\nAssociation, presented chief's tro\nphy to Grace White of Laurel, first\nprize essay winner.\nFire Recorder William E. Don\novan of Ellendale gave his fire re\nport for the month of October.\nBenediction by Rev. Jason Blun\ndon of Bridgeville.\n\nLocal Happenings\nBAKE The Band Boosters will\nhold a bake Saturday, November\n30th, at Green's Market, N. Walnut\nStreet, beginning at 10:00 o'clock.\nBAKE The Band Boosters will\nhold a bake Saturday, November j\n30th, at Green's Market, North Wal\nnut Street, beginning at 10 o'clock.\nHOMECOMING* Remember the\ndate, December 1st! Homecoming\nSunday at the First Presbyterian\nChurch at Milford. Invite your\nfriends.\nBAZAAR DINNERS\nAt St.\nJohns Parish Hall, Thursday, Dec\nember 5, ham and oysters dinner;\nFriday, December 6, oyster din\nner. Serving starts at 4 p. m.\nPrices: adults, $1.50, children, 75c.\nSHAWNEE SPEED KIDS The\nShawnee Speed Kids 4-H Club will\nhold a special meeting and dress\nrevue in Milford Century Club,\nMonday, December 2nd, at 7:30\np. m.\nCHRISTMAS CONCERT The\nAvenue Sanctuary Choir will pre\nsent their annual Christmas Con\ncert, Sunday, December 22nd, at 4\np. m., in Avenue Methodist Church,\nMilford.\nALCOHOL TROUBLES Alco\nhol troubling you? Genuine, con\nstructive help is yours for asking\nat Grange Hall, 8:30 p. m., Dec. 6.\nOnly charge is sincere desire for\nrelief.\nTHANKSGIVING^ DINNER\u2014 The\nW.S.C.S. of Milford Neck Church\nwill serve Turkey Dinner with all\nthe trimmings on Thanksgiving\nDay. Serving will be from 12 noon\nto 6:00 p. m. Adults, $1.50. Chil\ndren, $.75. Plan to eat your Thanks\ngiving Dinner with us then.\nTHANKSGIVING* A Thanks\ngiving Communion Service will be\nconducted in the Chapel of Avenue\nMethodist Church, by the pastor,\nRev. Robert E. Green, Thursday,\nNovember 28th, 9:00 a. m. All per\nsons desiring to receive Holy Com\nmunion on Thanksgiving Day are\nwelcome.\n\nFiftieth Wedding\nAnniversary\nThe family of Mr. and Mrs. Roy\nSapp invite relatives and friends\nto \"Open House\" at their residence\nSunday, December 1st, from 2 to 5\np. m., to honor their 50th Wedding\nAnniversary.\n\nLight Co. Officials\nAre Entertained\nOfficials of the Delaware Power\nLight Company were enthusiastic\nally welcomed to Millsboro at a\ncommunity-wide banquet recently,\nat Sam's Restaurant, Millsboro.\nDuring the meeting, Harley B.\nMitchell, president of the C. of C.\nspoke in behalf of the business\nmen and expressed appreciation to\nthe power company for their de\ncision to locate their 30 million\ndollar Indian River power plant\nin the Millsboro area.\nMr. Mitchell presented Mr. Nel\nson with honorary membership in\nthe C. of C. and assured the com\npany's president that the Mills\nboro businessmen would gladly as\nsist the employees of the utility\nfirm in taking up residences in the\nMillsboro community.\nDuring Mr. Nelson's remarks,\nvarious reasons for selection of\nthe Millsboro site were outlined.\nMr. Nelson said the friendliness of\nthe Millsooro people was a contrib\nuting factor.\nOther factors considered were\nthe large tract of land available,\nthe presence of the Indian River,\nnearn essof transportation, avail\nability of labor and other consider\nations.\nC. Robert Godfrey was master of\nceremonies and introduced various\ncivic group representatives who\nbrought greetings from their re\nspective groups within the com\nmunity.\nIntroduced were: Clarence Lin\ngo, Sr., president, Sussex County\nLevy Court, Joseph C. Lingo, chief\nMillsboro Fire Co., and member\nof Millsboro Town Council; Gran\nville Messick, president, Millsboro\nSchool Board: Raymond S. Goslee,\npresident, Millsboro P. T. A.; W.\nEdgar Timmons, president, Board\nof Stewards, Grace Methodist\nChurch; the Rev. Elmer P. Baker,\nrector, St. Mark's Episcopal Chur\nch; Elton P. Godfrey, commander,\nIndian River Post No. 22, Ameri\ncan Legion: Frederick Hudson,\ncommander, Sussex Memorial Post\nNo. 7422, VFW; Mayor Sanders P.\nDarden and Postmaster Roy E.\nJones, president, Millsboro Town\nCommissioners; Harley W. Moore,\npresident Millsboro Lions Club;\nSamuel Timmons, president Mills\nboro Kiwanis Club; and Jesse\nJones immediate past president,\nGeorgetown-Millsboro Rotary Club.\nHarry Long, Supt., Indian River\nPower Station, spoke and intro\nduced these D. P. L. Co. officials\nand personnel: Marvin Gibbons,\nresults engineer: Ralph Marsh,\nsupt. of mechanical maintenance;\nFrancis Looymans, electrical main\ntenance he#d; David Winslow, as\nsistant plant supt. Ray Taylor,\nJames Wimbrow, and Andre Dane,\nshift engineers.\nAlso introduced were three repre\nsentatives of the United Engineers\nContractors, Inc.; R. M. Edwards,\nsupt. of construction: Nelson\nSpence and Don Carswell.\nRobert Mullen, assistant man\nager of production for the ESPS\nCo., was introduced and sopke of\nthe plant's operations. He intro\nduced Henry Sterling, production\nmanager, ESPS Co.; and Mr. Nel\nson.\nU. S. Senator John J. Wil\nliams, was the main speaker of the\nevening and brought greetings to\nthe group not only as a Millsboro\nresident, but as well as from the\nCongress in Washington.\nRev. Baker gave the invocation\nand Miss Harriett Nichols played\nthe piano.\nPresident Mitchell appointed\nthree past nresidents of the Mills\nboro C. of C. as a nominating com\nmittee for the organization's slate\nof officers for 1958. They include;\nLeroy Monroe, W'esley Bullock, and\nEdward S. Cordrey.\nItems of a Purely\nPersonal Nature\nMiss Laurite Whitehead has\nbeen a patient in Memorial Hos\npital since Monday.\nMr. and Mrs. C. D. Holzmueller\nspent Thanksgiving in Suffolk, Va.,\nas the guests of Mr. and Mrs.\nGeorge V Beamon and children.\nMr. and Mrs. Clarence Welch\nare moving to the Edgar Welch\nhome on North Walnut street this\nweek.\nMrs. F. Burgette Short, who has\nbeen in Groton, Conn., for me past\nseveral weeks, returned to her\nhome Tuesday.\nMr. and Mrs. William O. Brimi\njoin and children of La Platte, Md.,\nare spending the holiday week-end\nwith Mr. and Mrs. George T. Mack\nlin.\nMr. and Mrs. Howard Postles had\nMr. and Mrs. Norman Touchton and\nMrs. J. W. Prettyman of Zion, Md.,\nas Thanksgiving Day guests. Mrs.\nPrettyman is remaining for a long\ner visit.\nMr. and Mrs. J. Postles Ham\nmond left for their new home in\nPompano Beach, Florida, on Tues-\nday and will spend the coming\nmonths there.\nMr. and Mrs. Henry Latchum and\nfamily of Newport News, Va., ar\nrived Thanksgiving Day and will\nremain until Saturday with Mr.\nand Mrs. J. Harry Latchum, Mr.\nand Mrs. J. Levin Latchum and\nfamily of Wilmington joined them\non the holiday.\nOBITUARY\nCARMINE\nMrs. Lillian M. Carmine, 68, died\nNovember 26 in the Nanticoke Me\nmorial Hospital in Seaford after a\nbrief illness. She was the daugh\nter of the late Joshua Littleton and\nEdith L. Blades of Seaford and the\nwidow of Joseph Carmine.\nSurviving are a son, Joseph Car\nmine of Seaford: four grandchil\ndren; one great-grandchild; a bro\nther, James Littleton of Kingston,\nN. Y. a half-brother, W. Leslie\nBlades of Milford, and a half-sister,\nMrs. Catherine Hearn of Baltimore.\nFuneral services will be held\nFriday at 2 p. m. in the Watson\nFuneral Home, Seaford, conducted\nby the Rev. James Birney, rector\nof St. I-uke's Episcopal Church,\nSeaford. Interment in Odd Fellows\nCemetery, Seaford.\nMillsboro Homemakers\nMillsboro Homemakers' Club\nmet Wednesday, November 20, at\nthe home of Mrs. Edgar Timmons,\nwith two visitors and twenty-nine\nmembers present.\nPlans were made for the Christ\nmas party to be held in the dining\nroom of Grace Methodist Church,\nThursday, December 19, at 12:00,\nwith a covered dish luncheon for\nmembers and guests.\nMrs. A. Wayne Burton and Mrs.\nNina Timmons gave an interest\ning demonstration on \"Christmas\nWrappings\".\nMrs. Frank Harrison, the newly\nelected president, appointed her\ncommittees: Citizenship, Mrs. Lyle\nFerris; Health, Mrs. John Can\nnon; Annual Reports, Mrs. Harold\nGardner: Publicity, Mrs. Clifford\nCahall; Recreation, Mrs. Davis\nCarlisle; Family Life, Mrs. Arling\nRemel; Safety, Mrs. Donald Cars\nwell; International Relations, Mrs.\nJohn Phillips; Outstanding Re\nward, Mrs. A. Wayne Burton; Sun\nshine, Mrs. George R. Hickman;\nChaplain and Historian, Mrs. Ed\nward McCabe.\nContributing to the Muscular\nDystrophy Drive and \"CARE\"\npackages to Hungary are among\nthe club's benevolent projects.\nThe club will meet in January\nat Zoar Community House with a\ncovered dish luncheon at 12:30.\nMrs. Davis Carlisle will be the hos\ntess. At that time the new officers\nfor '58-'59 will be installed.\nNews From\nHaskells Office\nU. S. Representative Harry G.\nHaskell, Jr. (R-Del) will make one\nof the two major speeches at a\nthree day special Franklin Insti\ntute Symposium on the Nation's\nserious Air Traffic problem to be\nheld in the Grand Ballroom of the\nSheraton Hotel in Philadelphia on\nDecember 16th, 17th, and 18th.\nThe symposium will, discuss the\nair traffic problems and the action\nrequired to solve them. Congress\nman (Haskell, who has been a lead\ner in the Congress for a better nat\nional aviation program, will pro\npose an aviation program for Con\ngressional action next year. Con\ngressman Haskell will speak on\nTuesday evening, December 17th.\nThe Nation's top aviation leaders\nwill participate in the symposium\nand will be drawn from the Air\nCarrier Field, State and Federal\nGovernment agencies, airport man\nagers, equipment manufacturers\nand various trade associations and\ntechnical societies.\nMr. E. R. (Pete) Quesada, Chair\nman of the Airways Modernization\nBoard will be the principal speak\ner on Monday night, December\n16th. The Airways Modernization\nBoard was established by legisla\ntion during the last Session of\nCongress and approved by the\nPresident on August 14th. Con\ngressman Haskell co-sponsored the\nlegislation in the Congress. Mr.\nQuesada will discuss the role of\nthe Airways Modernization Board\nin United States Aviation\u2014present\nand future.\nOther addresses will be made by\nMr. James Anast, acting Technical\nDirector of the Airways Moderni\nzation Board, Mr. Milton Arnold,\nVice President. Operation and En\ngineering, Air Transport Associa\ntion, and Mr. Louis Rothschild.\nUnder Secretary of Commerce and\na member of the Airways Moderni\nzation Board.\nSam Mitchell of Roslyn, L. I.,\nwas the guest of James R, Dra\nper the past week-end.\nMrs. Carleton Fooks with Mr.\nand Mrs. Robert Redden of Dover\nspent Thanksgiving in Philadel\nphia.\nMajor James V. Beckett and Miss\nMary Tezak of Arlington, Va., were\nweek-end guests of Mr. and Mrs.\nHarry Rust.\nMiss Carolee Green arrived home\nWednesday to spend the holiday\nweek-end with her parents, Rev\nerend and Mrs. Robert E. Green.\nMiss Green is a student at Leban\non College.\nMr. and Mrs. David A. Clements,\nJr., Mrs. Jane Smith and children\nof Dover were Thanksgiving Day\nguests of Mr. and Mrs. Maurice\nBower at their home in Milling\nton, N. J.\nMr. and Mrs. John C. Jewell, Mrs.\nClarence Jewell, Mrs. James Can\nnon, Miss Thelma Jewell and Miss\nMary Travis spent Thanksgiving\nDay in Centre Square, Pa., as the\nguests of Mr. and Mrs. Leroy Buck\nwaiter,\nMr. and Mrq. Huntley M. Toyer,\nafter spending the past six months\nat their summer residence at Re\nhoboth Beach, accompanied by Miss\nMay Watson, returned home this\npast week-end. They left on Tues\nday for Wilmingtou where they\nwill spend Thanksgiving and the\ncoming two weeks as guests of Mr.\nand Mrs. H. Ross Watson.\nOBITUARY\nLYNCH\nLemuel J. Lynch, 79, a retired\nmarine engineer, died November\n25 in the Beebe Hospital, Lewes,\nafter a short Illness.\nHe is survived by his wife, Mrs.\nCarrie E. Lynch of Lewes; a son,\nLonnie Lynch of Philadelphia: a\ndaugnter, Mrs. Doris Kline of Phil\nadelphia; a step-daughter, Mrs.\nDelores Jaul of Long Island, N. Y.\n12 grandchildren, and five great\ngrandchildren.\nFuneral services were held on\nThursday from St. George's Meth\nodist Church in Clarksville with\nthe Rev. Perry O. Hill officiating.\nInterment in St. George's Ceme\ntery.\nPUSEY\nG. Irving Pusey, 64, died at his\nhome in Riverdale, November 26,\nfollowing a heart attack. He was a\nretired superintendent of the Phil\nadelphia Transit Company'and a\nmember of the William B. Snyder\nLodge No. 419, AF and AM, Col\nlingsdale, Pa.\nHe is survived by his wife, Kath\nryn Pusey of Riverdale: a daugh\nter, Mrs. Virginia Long of Laurel,\nMd.; a son, AVarren Pusey of Sil\nver Spring, Md. three grandchil\ndren; and a brother, W. E. Pusey\nof Georgetown.\nThe funeral will be Saturday at\n2 p. m. at the Marvil Funeral Home,\nDarby, Pa., with the Rev. Dr.\nThomas C. Mulligan, pastor of\nGrace Methodist Church, George\ntown, officiating.\n\nWILLARD\nMrs. May D. Willard, 86, a na\ntive of Lewes, died November 26 at\nher home, 1101 West Sixth street,\nWilmington. She was the widow of\nHorace Willard of Lewes, and had\nbeen living in Wilmington since her\nhusband's death. She had been ill\nfor several months.\nShe was the daughter of the late\nJacob Marshall and Ella Coleman\nMarshall of Lewes. Surviving are\none daughter, Mrs. Anna Ryan of\nErie, Pa.; one son, Emil Willard of\nOdessa, and two brothers, George\nMarshall of Lewes Beach, and Ja\ncob Marshall of Wilmington.\nThe funeral will be held on Sat\nurday in the Atkins Funeral Home,\nLewes, conducted by the Rev.\nFrank L. Moon, rector of St. Peter's\nEpiscopal Church, Lewes. Inter\nment in Lewes Presbyterian Cem\netery.\nISAACS\nCharles H. Isaacs, Sr., 83, died\nNovember 24, at his residence on\nthe Seaford-Bridgeville Highway.\nHe had been in poor health for the\npast four years.\nA native of Greenwood and son\nof the late Charles T. and Emma\nStattes Isaacs, he had lived in the\nSeaford area for many years.\nA farmer and dealer in live stock\nhe was also active in Republican\npolitics and had served as county\ncommitteeman and also a term as\nSussex County Coroner.\nBesides his wife, Mrs. Cora Can\nnon Isaacs, he leaves three sons,\nLewis, Russell E., and Charles H.,\nJr., all of Seaford; and a daughter,\nMrs. Nellie Nichols, of Salisbury,\nand one granddaughter.\nThe funeral was held on Sunday\nat 2 p. m. in the Watson Funeral\nHome, Seaford. The Rev. Walter\nH. Stone, Mt. Olivetti Methodist\nChurch, officiating. Interment in\nOdd Fellows Cemetery, Seaford.\nZIRKER\nMrs. Ada L. Zirker, 78, a native\nof Rehoboth RD, died November 25\nat her home in Roslyn, Pa. She was\nborn and raised in the Lewes vicin\nity, the daughter of the late Jos\neph Hart and Matilda Lynch Hart\nof Rehoboth RD. She was the wife\nof Charles Zirker.\nIn addition to her husband, she\nis survived by two brothers,\nThomas Hart of Lewes-Millsboro\nHighway, and George Hart of Fort\nLauderdale, Fla., and Ocean City,\nN. J.; and one sister, Mrs. Mary\nSchmierer of Lewes: also many\nnephews and nieces in the Lewes\narea.\nFuneral services will be held to\nday at 2 p. m. in the Atkins Fu\nneral Home, Lewes, conducted by\nthe Re.'. A. Edward Dougherty, pas\ntor of the Bethel Methodist Church,\nLewes. Interment in the Lewes\nMethodist Cemetery.\nOBITUARY\nMARVEL\nMrs. Lillie Marie Marvel died\nSaturday morning, November 23,\nat her residence on Front street,\nSeaford, after a long illness. Her\nlate husband, J. Woodie Marvel of\nSeaford, died last year.\nShe was a member of St. John's\nMethodist Church and of the Mary\nL. Hopkins Bible Class. Surviving\nare several nieces and a nephew.\nFuneral services were held on\nNovember 26 at the Watson Funer\nal Home, Seaford. The Rev. Wil\nliam O. Hackett of St. John's\nChurch, officiating. Interment in\nthe Odd Fellows Cemetery, Sea\nford.\nADAM\nFuneral services for Mrs. Eliza\nbeth Adam, age 74 years, wife of\nJoseph Adam of Milford, was held\nfrom the St. John's Catholic Church\non Monday, November 25th, at\n10:00 a. m.\nInterment was in the Odd Fel\nlows Cemetery. The rosary was re\ncited by the Rev. John J. Corrigan\nSunday evening at 7:45 from the\nLofland Funeral Home. Mrs. Adam\npassed away in the Milford Memo\nrial Hospital on Thursday, Novem\nber 21, 1957. She was survived by\nher husband, Joseph Adam and two\nsons, Anton, of Milford, and Joseph\nJ. Adam of Linwood, Pa., and nine\ngrandchildren.\nMORGAN\nMrs. Annie Carey Morgan, 78,\nwidow of Wilbert Morgan, died at\nher home in Burrsville, near Har\nrington, Friday, November 22, af\nter a few weeks' illness. She was\nborn in Bridge ville.\nSurviving are six children: Mrs.\nRussell Brown, Harrington; Mrs.\nHarry Jackson, Montchanin; Ro\nland, Hamden, Conn.; Calvert, Mil\nford; James, Greenwood; Clinton,\nHarrington; 10 grandchildren and\n16 great-grandchildren.\nServi\u00e7es were held in the Boyer\nFuneral Home, Harrington, on\nNovember 26,. The Rev. John An\nderson, pastor of Burrsville Meth\nodist Church, officiating. Inter\nment in Hollywood Cemetery.\nATTIX\nEugene Clark Attix, 68, died No\nvember 24 at his home in Rising\nSun from the effects of a heart\ncondition. He was an office em\nployee of the Motor Vehicle De\npartment at Dover and formerly\nhad been engaged in farming and\ncarpentering.\nHe was born at Kenton, and is\nsurvived by his wife, Sarah J. At\ntix two-children, Mrs. Anna Stev\nens, Wilmington; Mrs. Mary C.\nBurton, Rehoboth Beach; three\ngrandchildren, two sisters, Mrs.\nEdith A. Carl, Wilmington, and\nMrs. Belle Palmer, Kenton.\nThe funeral was held Wednesday\nat 2 p. m. from the Calvary Church\nof the Nazarene in Dover. The\nRev. Charles Hallman officiating.\nInterment in Odd Fellows Ceme\ntery, Smyrna.\nHUSTON\nGeorge R. Huston, 51, owner and\noperator of Huston's News Agency,\nSeaford, died Sunday, November\n24, of a heart attack while as\nsisting in the delivery of the Sun\nday newspapers.\nHe was a son of the late James\nRobert and Edna Joselyn Huston,\na graduate of Seaford High School\nwhere he was a star athlete. He\nalso attended Bucknell University.\nHe belonged to the Seiford Lions\nClub and St. John's Methodist\nChurch.\nBesides his wife, Mrs. Nell E.\nHuston, he leaves a daughter. Miss\nCarol Huston and a son, James\nRobert Huston, all at home.\nServices were held Wednesday\nat 2 p. m. in the Watson Funeral\nHome in Seaford. The Rev. W. O.\nHackett of St. John's Church, offi\nciating. Burial in Odd Fellews\nCemetery, Seaford.\nWALTER\nJohn Gum Walter, .48, poultry\nman and farmer, died November 22\nat his home in Clarksville, after\nan illness of four months.\nHe was a member of the Mill\nville Methodist Church and was\na trustee of the church and taught\nSunday School there. He was a\nmember of Doric Lodge No. 30,\nAF AM, Millville, and a direc\ntor of the First National Bank,\nFrankford. He was a 32nd degree\nMason.\nHe was the son of Mrs. Mattie\nBennett Horsey, Frankford, and\nthe late John G. Walter. Besides\nhis mother he is survived by his\nwife, Mrs. Dorothy Evans Walter,\na son, John Jehu Walter, two sis\nters, Mrs. Mattie Cropper, Ocean\nCity, Md., and Mrs. Helena Kirk,\nColorado Springs, Colo.\nThe funeral was held on Novem\nber 25, at 2 p. m. in the Watson\nand Gray Funeral Chapel, Prank\nford. The Rev. W. S. Grant, for\nmer pastor of the Millville Meth\nodist Church, and the Rev. Melvin\nWheatley, Rehoboth, officiating.\nInterment in St. George's Ceme\ntery, Clarksville.\nFISH\nMrs. Bertha Mae Fish, wife of\nHoward M. Fish, of Bridgeville,\ndied in the Milford Memorial Hos\npital early Sunday morning, fol\nlowing a prolonged illness. Before\nmoving to Bridgeville four months\nago, she and her husband had liv\ned for ten years in Federalsburg.\nBorn at Dagsboro 49 years ago,\nshe was the daughter of the late\nLemuel and Mollie Hudson Brumb\nley. For a number of years prior\nto her illness, Mrs. Fish was em\nployed by Maryland Plastics, Inc.,\nin Federalsburg.\nShe is survived by her husband,\nHoward M. Fish, of Bridgeville:\nfour'children, Wilmer L. and Har\nvey L. Toomey, of Federalsburg,\nMd., and Robert and Lucy Ann\nFish of Bridgevinlle, and by the\nfollowing sisters and brothers, Mrs.\nEdith Fisher, Ottie Brumbley, Mrs.\nClara Hitchens and Raymond\nBrumbley, all of Dagsboro, and\nJohn Brumbley of Millsboro.\nFuneral services were held at\nthe Framptom Funeral Home in\nFederalsburg on Wednesday af\nternoon at 1 o'clock with Rev.\nDonald O. ^Clendaniel, \"pastor of\nUnion Methodist Church, officiating.\nInterment in Red Men's Cemetery\nat Dagsboro.\nHappenings of Interest\nThroughout Delaware\nORGAN RECITAL At Lincoln\nChurch, Thursday, December 5th,\nat 7:45, with Rev. Elwood B. Eck\nhart. Pastor of Ellendale Church,\nat the console.\nLincoln W.S.C.S., Circle No. 3,\nMrs. Edward Fitzgerald, chairman,\nis in charge of the Recital. A treat\nwill be in store for all lovers of\nmusic. Come hear our new Ham\nmond Organ. A free will offering\nwill be taken, for the benefit of the\nSociety.\nCOSTLY SUPPORT \u2014A prison\nsentence was imposed by Judge W.\nMarion Stevenson in Juvenile\nCourt Dover, on a man who was\nin arrears in non-support payments\nand made no apparent effoft to at\ntend to the matter.\nJudge Stevenson commented\nthat the action was only the be\nginning and that similar action in\nother pending cases could be ex\npected unless the payments were\nmade in accordance with the order\nof the court.\nThomas Burris of Frederica, who\nfailed to maintain non-support pay\nments to his wife, was sentenced to\nserve six months in jail and pay a\nfine of $200.\n\nHospital Hostesses\nHospital Shop Hostesses for the\nMilford Memorial Hospital, Friday,\nNovember 29th through Thursday,\nDecember 4th.\nFriday, November 29th: After\nnoon, Mrs. J. J. Pearce; evening,\nMrs. Wm. De'linger.\nSaturday, November 30th: After\nnoon, Mrs. Carson Ward, Mrs.\nPrice Webb; evening, Mrs. Boyd\nHoutz.\nSunday, December 1st: After\nnoon, Mrs. Willard Pierce; even\ning, Mrs. Gilbert Murphy, Miss\nDorothy Derrickson.\nMonday, December 2nd: After\nnoon, Mrs. Carol Short, Mrs. How\nard French; evening, Mrs. Wm.\nClendaniel.\nTuesday, December 3rd: After\nnoon, Mrs. Nelson Hall, Mrs. Wm.\nThompson evening, Mrs. Anp\nWestphal.\nWednesday, December 4th: After\nnoon, Mrs. Ed Steiner, Mrs. John\nMcGee; evening, Mrs. Dallas Hit\nchens.\nThursday, December 5th; After\nMrs. Harry Frankel, Mrs.\nMrs.\nnoon,\nRobert Mercer; evening,\nCharles Ricker.\nHospital Cart Hostesses\u2014Friday,\nNovember 29th: Mrs. A1 Humes,\nMfs. Sim Richardsop Saturday,\nNovember 30th: Mrs. W. O. Lank\nford, Mary Lou Lankford; Monday,\nDecember 2nd: Mrs. Albert Peter\nman, Mrs. W. P. Poitz; Tuesday,\nDecember 3rd: Mrs. John Glenn,\nMrs. Leslie Dobson; Wednesday,\nNovember 4th; Mrs. Joe Kemp,\nMrs. Chuck Wright; Thursday,\nNovember 5th: Mrs. Clement Nevin,\nMrs. Alfred Passwaters; Friday,\nNovember 6th: Mrs. Joseph Pearce,\nSr., Mrs. Carlton Fooks.\nm\nMillwood H. D. Club\nThe monthly meeting of Millwood\nHome Demonstration Club will be\nheld in the hall on Wednesday, De\ncember 4, at 2 p. m.\nThis will be a Christmas party,\neach member to bring a gift to\nexchange: also a toy for the in\nmates at the Delaware Colony.\nThe club will give a party to the\ninmates at th^ colony on December\n18. More about this at the meeting.\nThe committee for the Christ\nmast party consists of Edith La\ncey, Mary Abbott, Annie Morris and\nBessie Swain. The committee for\ncakes and decorations is composed\nof Edith Kline and Winnie Lynch.\nSussex County\nFire Recorders Report\nFor the month of October, 1957,\nas submitted by William E. Dono\nvan, fire recorder.\nTotal alarms, 45: town, 20; rural.\n22; false. 1; other towns, 2.\nLoss, $27,700; covered by insur\nance, $16,050; net loss, $12,650;\ntown. $21,700; rural, $6,000.\nMen in service, 718: hours in ser\nvice, 35; total man hours, 2,351;\nmiles traveled, 238.\nFeet of hose used: 1 inch, 2,750;\nIVa inch. 2,000; 2% inch, 500.\nFeet of ladders raised, 239.\nType of Fires: Mercantile, 2;\ndwellings, 9; chimney, 9; auto, 4;\ngrass, 5; woods, 1; chicken house,\n1; miscellaneous, 14.\nCompany responding to most\nalarms, Georgetown (10).\nCompany having greatest loss,\nFrankford ($20,000).\nCompany having no fires: Indian\nRiver, Delmar and Gumboro.\nAmbulance Service; Trips. 89;\nmen in service, 175; hours in ser\nvice, 566; total man hours, 10,399;\ntotal miles traveled, 3,994.\n\nTrophy Grange Notes\nMrs. Eva Ellingsworth presented\nthe following program in Trophy\nGrange last Monday night:\nOpening song, \"Faith of Our Fa\nthers.\"\nReading, \"March to the Master,\"\nMrs. Ellingsworth.\nThe Farmer's Share of the Con\nsumers Dollars, Winfred Gruwell.\nReading, \"The Bridge Builders,\"\nAnnie I. Gow.\nQuiz on Grange Procedure, Mrs.\nCohee.\nReading,\nThe Pattern of the\nShingle,\" Rodney Biddle.\nJokes, Mrs. Reba Gruwell.\nHints for Homemakers, Dorothy\nHeyd.\nMy First Accident,\" Elmer Co\nhee.\nConundrums, Mrs. Cohee.\nClosing Song, \"Bringing in the\nSheaves.\"\nRefreshments were enjoyed by\nall.\nOn December 9, Mr. and Mrs.\nW T infred Gruwell and Mrs. Cohee\nwill be in charge of the Christmas\nprogram. There will be an ex\nchange of gifts as usual.\nCHRISTMAS SERVICE\nThe\nDover District Ministerial Associa\ntion of the Methodist Church will\nconduct their Christmas Service in\nthe Avenue Methodist Church, Mon\nday, December 2nd, at 11:00 a. m.\nRev. Roy L. Tawes, District Super\nintendent of Dover District, will\npreach a Christmas Sermon. Fol\nlowing the service a dinner will\nbe served in Fellowship Hall by\nthe ladies of the Church.\nMANSHIFTS ANNUAL DINNER\n\u2014The Manship Annual Thanksgiv\ning dinner will be served at Man\nship's Church House, 4 miles west\nof Felton, on Route 12, Thursday,\nNovember 28th. Starting at 12 o'\nclock noon, to 7:30 o'clock. Menu\nconsists of turkey, oysters, and\nall the trimmings, with dessert\nPrice, $1.60, children, $.50 and $.75.\nFor reservations call Felton 4\n4653 or 4-4250.\nTRAINING MEETING A Lead\ner Training meeting will be held\nfrom 1:00 to 3:00 p. m., December\n2, at the Viola Community Hall.\nThe subject will be\nReweaving of Wool\". Two leaders\nfrom each Home Demonstration\nClub in the county will attend and\ntake this information back to her\nindividual club.\nMiss Lois Korslund, Extension\nClothing Specialist and Mrs. Ruth\nAdams, Home Demonstration Ag\nent, will teach the subject matter\nat this meeting.\nInvisible\nSOCIAL SECURITY The So\ncial Security representative from\nthe Wilmington office, Mr. Joseph\nMenustik, on hjs regular visit to\nMilford, this Tuesday, interviewed\n20 local residents.\nRegular visits are made to this\narea to assist in the completion\nof applications for old age, sur\nvivors and disability insurance\nbenefits and to furnish informa\ntion! about social security. No\ncharge is made for this service.\nThe next visit to Milford will be\non Tuesday, December 3, at the\nCity Office Building, from 9:30 a.\nm. until 12 noon.\nKENT CLINICS December 2,\n1967: Well Child Conference, Do\nver, Health Unit, 414 S. State\nStreet, 1:00 p. m. Call Dover 5711,\nExt. 10 for appointments.\nDecember 3, 1957: Well Child\nConference, Smyrna (c>, Health\nUnit, E. Commerce Street, 2:00 p.\nm.; Venereal Disease Clinic, Mil\nford, Health Unit, Shore Theater\nBuilding, 11:30 a. m.-12:30 p. m.\nCrippled Children's Clinic, Dover,\nHealth Unit, 414 S. State Street,\n9:30 a. m.\nDecember 4, 1957: Chest Clinic,\nDover, Health Unit, 414 S. State\nStreet, 10:00 a. m. and 1:00 p. m.\nCHANGES NAME \u2014This year the\nAmerican Field Service is oper\nating for the first time in Seaford\nunder a new title, Americans\nAbroad.\nSchool officials point out that\nthe AFS program has brought for\neign exchange students to Seaford\nfor a year's study in the high\nschool. In return Seaford students\nhave spent summers in Norway,\nSweden, Italy, Greece, Germany\nand France.\nNow the AFS offers a new pro\ngram under which our students\nmay study from three to five\nmonths in schools of another coun\ntry, the officials add, noting that\nSeaford is eligible to enter the pro\ngram.\nSUSSEX CLINICS December\n2, 1957: Venereal Disease Clinic,\nGeorgetown, Health Unit, 605 E,\nMarket Street, 12:00 noon.\nDecember 3, 1957 Cancer Detec\ntion Center, Seaford, Nanticoke\nHospital. For women 25 years of\nage and over. Call Seaford 7786\nfor appointments.\nDecember 4. 1957: Well Child\nConference, Laurel (c) Health\nUnit, Pine Street, 10:00 a. m.\nLewes, Health Unit, 110 W. 3rd\nStreet, 1:00 p. m.; Prenatal Post\nnatal Clinic, Seaford (c), Nanti\ncoke Hospital, 10:00 a. m.\nDecember 5, 1957 Cancer Detec\ntion Center, Lewes, Beebe Hospital.\nFor women 25 years of age and\nover. Call Lewes 5311 for appoint\nments.\nLOW BIDDER\u2014Cluto Brothers.\nWyoming, was low bidder at the\nopening of bids by the Dover Board\nof Education Wednesday night for\nthe construction of an addition to\nthe Booker T. Washington School.\nTheir bid, including base bid and\nthree alternates, was $382,525.\nJames H. Wood, Dover, was sec\nond low, bidding $384,200 and John\nE. Healy and Sons, Wilmington,\nwas next with a bid of $385,338.\nThe other four of the seven bids\nreceived were: J. R. Dashiell, Sal\nisbury.Md., $386,775; Leonard Pe\nvar Co., Kennett Square, Pa., $403,\noig; Facciolo Construction Co.,\nVllmington, $403,921.18, and H.\nClay Phillips Sons, Middletown,\n$404,873.\nThe bids were referred to the\narchitect, Walter Carlson, Wil\nmington, for study and recommen\ndation.\nFOOTBALL BANQUET\nThe\nDover Junior Chamber of Com\nmerce is pointing with pride to the\ngreatest High School Football\nBanquet ever to be held in the\nState of Delaware. W!t h flittering\nstars of the Gridiron as headlin\ners, the High School Football Team\nwill enjoy a never-to-be-forgotten\nevening on December 5th at 7:00\np. m., at The Hub.\nAround what other banquet table\ndo you have Tommy Mont, Head\nFootball Coach of the University\nof Maryland; Jack Hennemier,\nLine Coach of the University of\nMaryland; \"Wild Man\" Willey of\nthe Philadelphia Eagles; Com\nmander John E. McQuary, Plebe\nFootball Coach of the United\nStates Naval Academy: and Lt.\nJames Carrington, former All\nAmerican Guard.\nThere will be many more stars\nthere to thrill even the \"football\ners of yester-year\".","height":"25404","width":"20493"}}
